I've confirmed a bug. The logic in `queue_pages_range()` is flawed. If `walk_page_range()` is interrupted early during the walk, specifically before the first VMA has been processed (during the attempt to acquire the VMA write lock in `process_vma_walk_lock()`), the function incorrectly returns `-EFAULT` instead of `-EINTR`. This happens because `qp.first` is not set.

The intended behavior, as indicated by the added docstring and the commit message "Ensure users handle EINTR correctly and do not ignore it", is to return `-EINTR` when a signal interrupts the page walk. However, the current code, specifically the `if (!qp.first)` check in `queue_pages_range()`, overrides the `-EINTR` with `-EFAULT` when the interruption occurs before any VMA has been touched.

This `-EFAULT` return is incorrect and loses the information that the syscall was interrupted. This is especially bad in `sys_mbind` which calls `queue_pages_range` with `MPOL_MF_INVERT | MPOL_MF_WRLOCK`. The `mbind` syscall will return `-EFAULT`, which is not what userspace expects.

Furthermore, I have verified that this issue is isolated to this specific scenario. Other instances using `walk_page_range()` correctly propagate the error, specifically the functions that use `PGWALK_WRLOCK`:
