tion/mm/process_addrs.rst-94-* Obtain a VMA write lock via :c:func:`!vma_start_write` for each VMA you wish to\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst:95:  modify, which will be released automatically when :c:func:`!mmap_write_unlock` is\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-96-  called.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-97-* If you want to be able to write to **any** field, you must also hide the VMA\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-98-  from the reverse mapping by obtaining an **rmap write lock**.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-99-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-100-VMA locks are special in that you must obtain an mmap **write** lock **first**\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-101-in order to obtain a VMA **write** lock. A VMA **read** lock however can be\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-102-obtained without any other lock (:c:func:`!lock_vma_under_rcu` will acquire then\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-103-release an RCU lock to lookup the VMA for you).\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-104-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-105-This constrains the impact of writers on readers, as a writer can interact with\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-106-one VMA while a reader interacts with another simultaneously.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-107-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-108-.. note:: The primary users of VMA read locks are page fault handlers, which\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-109-          means that without a VMA write lock, page faults will run concurrent with\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-110-          whatever you are doing.\n--\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-800-required for lookup. This is abstracted by :c:func:`!lock_vma_under_rcu` which\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-801-is the interface a user should use.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-802-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-803-Writing requires the mmap to be write-locked and the VMA lock to be acquired via\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-804-:c:func:`!vma_start_write`, however the write lock is released by the termination or\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-805-downgrade of the mmap write lock so no :c:func:`!vma_end_write` is required.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-806-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-807-All this is achieved by the use of per-mm and per-VMA sequence counts, which are\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-808-used in order to reduce complexity, especially for operations which write-lock\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-809-multiple VMAs at once.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-810-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-811-If the mm sequence count, :c:member:`!mm->mm_lock_seq` is equal to the VMA\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-812-sequence count :c:member:`!vma->vm_lock_seq` then the VMA is write-locked. If\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-813-they differ, then it is not.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-814-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst:815:Each time the mmap write lock is released in :c:func:`!mmap_write_unlock` or\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-816-:c:func:`!mmap_write_downgrade`, :c:func:`!vma_end_write_all` is invoked which\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-817-also increments :c:member:`!mm->mm_lock_seq` via\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-818-:c:func:`!mm_lock_seqcount_end`.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-819-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-820-This way, we ensure that, regardless of the VMA's sequence number, a write lock\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-821-is never incorrectly indicated and that when we release an mmap write lock we\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-822-efficiently release **all** VMA write locks contained within the mmap at the\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-823-same time.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-824-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-825-Since the mmap write lock is exclusive against others who hold it, the automatic\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-826-release of any VMA locks on its release makes sense, as you would never want to\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-827-keep VMAs locked across entirely separate write operations. It also maintains\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-828-correct lock ordering.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-829-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-830-Each time a VMA read lock is acquired, we increment :c:member:`!vma.vm_refcnt`\n--\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-851-indicating a writer is cleared. From this point on, VMA's sequence number will\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-852-indicate VMA's write-locked state until mmap write lock is dropped or downgraded.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-853-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-854-This clever combination of a reference counter and sequence count allows for\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-855-fast RCU-based per-VMA lock acquisition (especially on page fault, though\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-856-utilised elsewhere) with minimal complexity around lock ordering.\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-857-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-858-mmap write lock downgrading\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-859----------------------------\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-860-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-861-When an mmap write lock is held one has exclusive access to resources within the\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-862-mmap (with the usual caveats about requiring VMA write locks to avoid races with\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-863-tasks holding VMA read locks).\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-864-\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-865-It is then possible to **downgrade** from a write lock to a read lock via\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst:866::c:func:`!mmap_write_downgrade` which, similar to :c:func:`!mmap_write_unlock`,\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-867-implicitly terminates all VMA write locks via :c:func:`!vma_end_write_all`, but\nDocumentation/mm/process_addrs.rst-868-impor