y_policy.rst-127-\tvirtual addresses that map the shared object.  However, unlike\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-128-\tVMA policies, which can be considered to be an attribute of a\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-129-\trange of a task's address space, shared policies apply\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-130-\tdirectly to the shared object.  Thus, all tasks that attach to\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-131-\tthe object share the policy, and all pages allocated for the\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-132-\tshared object, by any task, will obey the shared policy.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-133-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-134-\tAs of 2.6.22, only shared memory segments, created by shmget() or\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-135-\tmmap(MAP_ANONYMOUS|MAP_SHARED), support shared policy.  When shared\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-136-\tpolicy support was added to Linux, the associated data structures were\n--\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-372-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-373-We can avoid taking an extra reference during the usages listed above as\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-374-follows:\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-375-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-376-1) we never need to get/free the system default policy as this is never\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-377-   changed nor freed, once the system is up and running.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-378-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-379-2) for querying the policy, we do not need to take an extra reference on the\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-380-   target task's task policy nor vma policies because we always acquire the\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-381-   task's mm's mmap_lock for read during the query.  The set_mempolicy() and\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst:382:   mbind() APIs [see below] always acquire the mmap_lock for write when\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-383-   installing or replacing task or vma policies.  Thus, there is no possibility\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-384-   of a task or thread freeing a policy while another task or thread is\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-385-   querying it.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-386-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-387-3) Page allocation usage of task or vma policy occurs in the fault path where\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-388-   we hold them mmap_lock for read.  Again, because replacing the task or vma\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-389-   policy requires that the mmap_lock be held for write, the policy can't be\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-390-   freed out from under us while we're using it for page allocation.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-391-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-392-4) Shared policies require special consideration.  One task can replace a\n--\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-449-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-450-Queries the \"task/process memory policy\" of the calling task, or the\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-451-policy or location of a specified virtual address, depending on the\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-452-'flags' argument.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-453-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-454-See the get_mempolicy(2) man page for more details\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-455-\nDocumen