licy.rst-477-task's address range. The system call updates the home node only for the existing\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-478-mempolicy range. Other address ranges are ignored. A home node is the NUMA node\n--\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-483-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-484-Memory Policy Command Line Interface\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-485-====================================\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-486-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-487-Although not strictly part of the Linux implementation of memory policy,\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-488-a command line tool, numactl(8), exists that allows one to:\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-489-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-490-+ set the task policy for a specified program via set_mempolicy(2), fork(2) and\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-491-  exec(2)\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-492-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst:493:+ set the shared policy for a shared memory segment via mbind(2)\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-494-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-495-The numactl(8) tool is packaged with the run-time version of the library\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-496-containing the memory policy system call wrappers.  Some distributions\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-497-package the headers and compile-time libraries in a separate development\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-498-package.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-499-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-500-.. _mem_pol_and_cpusets:\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-501-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-502-Memory Policies and cpusets\nDocumentation/admin-guide/mm/numa_memory_policy.rst-503-===========================\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-47-Cpusets constrain the CPU and Memory placement of tasks to only\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-48-the resources within a task's current cpuset.  They form a nested\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-49-hierarchy visible in a virtual file system.  These are the essential\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-50-hooks, beyond what is already present, required to manage dynamic\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-51-job placement on large systems.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-52-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-53-Cpusets use the generic cgroup subsystem described in\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-54-Documentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cgroups.rst.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-55-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-56-Requests by a task, using the sched_setaffinity(2) system call to\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst:57:include CPUs in its CPU affinity mask, and using the mbind(2) and\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-58-set_mempolicy(2) system calls to include Memory Nodes in its memory\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-59-policy, are both filtered through that task's cpuset, filtering out any\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-60-CPUs or Memory Nodes not in that cpuset.  The scheduler will not\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-61-schedule a task on a CPU that is not allowed in its cpus_allowed\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-62-vector, and the kernel page allocator will not allocate a page on a\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-63-node that is not allowed in the requesting task's mems_allowed vector.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-64-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-65-User level code may create and destroy cpusets by name in the cgroup\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-66-virtual file system, manage the attributes and permissions of these\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-67-cpusets and which CPUs and Memory Nodes are assigned to each cpuset,\n--\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-340-By default, both kinds of memory spreading are off, and memory\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-341-pages are allocated on the node local to where the task is running,\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-342-except perhaps as modified by the task's NUMA mempolicy or cpuset\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-343-configuration, so long as sufficient free memory pages are available.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-344-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-345-When new cpusets are created, they inherit the memory spread settings\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-346-of their parent.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-347-\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-348-Setting memory spreading causes allocations for the affected page\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-349-or slab caches to ignore the task's NUMA mempolicy and be spread\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst:350:instead.    Tasks using mbind() or set_mempolicy() calls to set NUMA\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-351-mempolicies will not notice any change in these calls as a result of\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-352-their containing task's memory spread settings.  If memory spreading\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-353-is turned off, then the currently specified NUMA mempolicy once again\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-354-applies to memory page allocations.\nDocumentation/admin-guide/cgroup-v1/cpusets.rst-3